8 [ electric utilities - GET Over Congestion (Grid
9 Enhancing Technology Over Congestion) Act - use of
10 technologies - consultation with large load users -
11 Corporation Commission - integrated resource plans
12 - cost recovery – codification - effective date ]
13
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
17 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 860 of Title 17, unless there is
18 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
19 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "GET Over
20 Congestion (Grid Enhancing Technology Over Congestion) Act".
21 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 861 of Title 17, unless there is
23 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24 A. As used in this section:
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3183 Page 1

1 1. "Advanced power flow controllers" means technologies that
2 modulate circuit impedance or other electrical properties to reroute
3 power flows and relieve congestion;
4 2. "Advanced transmission technology" means a technology that
5 increases the capacity, efficiency, or reliability of electric
6 transmission infrastructure, including grid-enhancing technologies
7 (GETs) such as dynamic line rating, advanced power flow controllers,
8 and topology optimization; high-performance conductors; and other
9 technologies designed to reduce transmission congestion;
10 3. "Congestion" means a condition in which a lack of
11 transmission line capacity prevents the delivery of the lowest cost
12 electricity dispatched to meet load at a specific location;
13 4. "Dynamic line rating" means a system that uses real-time or
14 forecasted weather and operating conditions, including wind speed
15 and direction, to determine the transfer capacity;
16 5. "Grid-enhancing technologies" or "GETs" means advanced
17 transmission technologies that increase the usable capacity of
18 existing transmission infrastructure through hardware, software, or
19 operational tools including dynamic line rating, advanced power flow
20 controllers, topology optimization, and related technologies;
21 6. "High performance conductors" means a conductor used in an
22 electric transmission system, including carbon-fiber conductors,
23 composite core conductors, and superconductors, and where:
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3183 Page 2

1 a. the conductor has a direct current electrical
2 resistance that is at least ten percent (10%) lower
3 than an aluminum conductor steel reinforced (ACSR)
4 conductor with a similar diameter and weight,
5 b. the conductor has an energy carrying capacity at least
6 seventy-five percent (75%) greater than ACSR
7 conductors of a similar diameter and weight, or
8 c. the conductor has a coefficient of thermal expansion
9 at least thirty percent (30%) less than ACSR
10 conductors of a similar diameter and weight;
11 7. "Integrated resource plan" or "IRP" means a utility's plan
12 as further defined and established in the Oklahoma Corporation
13 Commission's administrative rules found at OAC 165:35-37 to ensure
14 that sufficient supply-side and demand-side resources are available
15 to meet its obligation to serve and to achieve public policy
16 objectives, including those prescribed by law, rule, or Commission
17 IRP filing, a rate case, or other proceeding in which an electric
18 utility proposes additions or expansions to the transmission system;
19 8. "Large load user" means an electric customer whose existing
20 or anticipated load materially contributes to transmission
21 congestion or necessitates transmission upgrades;
22 9. "Topology optimization" means software that identifies
23 switching configurations to reroute electricity and alleviate
24 transmission constraints; and
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3183 Page 3

1 10. "Utility" means an investor-owned electric utility subject
2 to the ratemaking and integrated resource planning authority of the
3 Oklahoma Corporation Commission, and does not include electric
4 cooperatives, municipal utilities, or other non-investor-owned
5 providers.
6 B. A utility shall analyze, as part of its planning process and
7 in coordination with stakeholders where practicable, the cost-
8 effectiveness and deployment timeline of advanced transmission
9 technologies and GETs. A utility shall analyze:
10 1. The cost effectiveness and timetable for deployment of
11 advanced transmission technologies as an alternative strategy to
12 meet electric system needs; and
13 2. Whether the technologies would:
14 a. increase transmission capacity,
15 b. increase transmission efficiency,
16 c. reduce transmission system congestion,
17 d. reduce curtailment of energy generation resources,
18 e. increase reliability,
19 f. reduce the risk of igniting wildfire,
20 g. increase resiliency, or
21 h. increase capacity to connect new energy resources.
22 C. A utility may consult with large load users to identify
23 opportunities for voluntary collaboration, cost-sharing, or
24 customer-funded pilot deployment of GETs to reduce congestion and
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3183 Page 4

1 mini mize impacts to the general rate base. The Corporation
2 Commission shall encourage a utility to include the deployment of
3 advanced transmission technologies in an integrated resource plan.
4 In an integrated resource plan, a utility shall:
5 1. Analyze congestion hotspots to cost-effectively maximize the
6 delivery of energy resources in the near term, including:
7 a. identifying the ten most congested locations on the
8 entity's transmission system,
9 b. estimating the frequency of congestion at each
10 location and the increased cost to ratepayers
11 resulting from the substitution of higher-priced
12 electricity,
13 c. evaluating the technical feasibility and estimate the
14 cost of installing one or more advanced transmission
15 technologies to address each instance of grid
16 congestion, and
17 d. proposing an implementation plan, including a schedule
18 and cost estimate, to install advanced transmission
19 technologies at each congestion point;
20 2. Include the results of the analysis described in paragraph 1
21 of this subsection and the analysis described in subsection B of
22 this section in the filing to the Commission; and
23 3. Include a summary of its existing and planned advanced
24 transmission technologies.
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3183 Page 5

1 D. If the Commission determines, based on the analysis provided
2 by the utility under subsections B and C of this section, that the
3 deployment of advanced transmission technologies is cost effective,
4 the Commission shall approve the utility's recovery of the prudently
5 incurred costs of the advanced transmission technologies.
6 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
7 Passed the House of Representatives the 4th day of March, 2026.
